# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-mineralogist
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-mineralogist/american-mineralogist] The journal was established in 1916, with the first issue appearing in July of that year, under the auspices of the *Philadelphia Mineralogical Society*, the *New York Mineralogical Club*, and the *Mineral Collectors' Association*.
[src:american-mineralogist/american-mineralogist] On December 30, 1919, the Mineralogical Society of America was formed and *American Mineralogist* became the society's journal.
[src:american-mineralogist/american-mineralogist] The *American Mineralogist* is abstracted and indexed in Chemical Abstracts, the Science Citation Index, GeoRef, and INSPEC.
[src:american-mineralogist/american-mineralogist] According to *Journal Citation Reports*, the journal has a 2011 impact factor of 2.100.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] The two principal databases that support the different products are CAplus and Registry.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] CAS References consists of bibliographic information and abstracts for all articles in chemical journals worldwide, and chemistry-related articles from all scientific journals, patents, and other scientific publications.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] As of 2023, the CAS Registry contains information on more than 200 million organic and inorganic substances, and about 70 million protein and nucleic acid sequences.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] The sequence information comes from CAS and GenBank, produced by the National Institutes of Health.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] The chemical information is produced by CAS, and is prepared by the CAS Registry System, which identifies each compound with a specific CAS registry number, index name, and graphic representation of its chemical structure.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] The assignment of chemical names is done according to the chemical nomenclature rules for *CA* index names, which is slightly different from the internationally standard IUPAC names, according to the rules of IUPAC.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] CAS databases are available via two principal database systems, STN, and SciFinder.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] STN (Scientific & Technical Information Network) International is operated jointly by CAS and FIZ Karlsruhe, and is intended primarily for information professionals, using a command language interface.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] In addition to CAS databases, STN also provides access to many other databases, similar to Dialog.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] SciFinder is a database of chemical and bibliographic information.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] Originally it was available only as a client application (for both Windows and MacOS operating systems), a web version was released in 2008.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] By that time it had a graphical interface, and was able to do graphical searches for chemical structures and reactions (the first database to allow such functions), as well as keyword searches for literature in chemistry and related disciplines.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] SciFinder Scholar was a very similar a product developed for academic institutions, but discontinued in 2023.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] In 2017 the ACS released SciFinder-n as a web-only product with the same data content and improved user interface and search functions.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] SciFinder is considered as the best source of chemical information worldwide, with substantially larger number of relevant information sources than Web of Science or Scopus with Reaxys.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] However, due to its unique and unusual search functions, substantial training is needed in order to fully take advantage of SciFinder capabilities.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] The range is from 1907 to the present, including both serial and non-serial scientific and technical publications.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] *Beyond CASSI* lists abbreviated journal titles from early chemical literature and other historical reference sources.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] For many years, beginning in 1909, the offices of *Chemical Abstracts* were housed in various places on the Columbus, Ohio campus of Ohio State University, including McPherson Laboratory and Watts Hall.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] In 1965, CAS moved to a new 50-acre (200,000 m2) site on the west bank of the Olentangy River, just north of The Ohio State campus.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] This campus became well known in the Columbus area and famous as the site of many Columbus Symphony Orchestra pop concerts.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] In 2009, the campus consisted of three buildings.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] Noyes had enlarged the *Review of American Chemical Research*, an abstracting publication begun by Arthur Noyes in 1895 that was the forerunner of *Chemical Abstracts*.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] When it became evident that a separate publication containing these abstracts was needed, Noyes became the first editor of the new publication, *Chemical Abstracts*.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] Crane became the first Director of Chemical Abstracts Service when it became an American Chemical Society division in 1956.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] Crane had been *CA* editor since 1915, and his dedication was a key factor in its long-term success.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] Baker became the CAS Director upon Crane's retirement in 1958.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] According to CAS, his visionary view of CAS' potential "led to expansion, modernization, and the forging of international alliances with other information organizations." CAS was an early leader in the use of computer technology to organize and disseminate information.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] The CAS Chemical Registry System was introduced in 1965.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] CAS developed a unique registry number to identify chemical substances.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] Environmental Protection Agency and local fire departments around the world now rely on these numbers for the definite identification of substances.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] According to the ACS, this is the largest chemical substance database in the world.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] In 1965, CAS left their offices at OSU for a new headquarters north of campus.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] Ground was broken in 1971 for an expansion to the building designed by architects Brubaker/Brandt to accommodate the review of 400,000 new research reports printed each year.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] The 5-story 142,000 square foot building opened in May 1973.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] In 2007, the ACS designated its Chemical Abstracts Service subdivision an ACS National Historic Chemical Landmark in recognition of its significance as a comprehensive repository of research in chemistry and related sciences.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] In 2021, CAS rebranded along with a change in logo.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] The organization updated their mission to be more focused on dynamic responsiveness due to ongoing changes within scientific industries and communities.
[src:american-mineralogist/chemical-abstracts] In 2022, CAS announced the release of almost half a million CAS registry numbers under an open license in their Common Chemistry project.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] Crystallography is a broad topic, and many of its subareas, such as X-ray crystallography, are themselves important scientific topics.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] Crystallography ranges from the fundamentals of crystal structure to the mathematics of crystal geometry, including those that are not periodic or quasicrystals.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] At the atomic scale it can involve the use of X-ray diffraction to produce experimental data that the tools of X-ray crystallography can convert into detailed positions of atoms, and sometimes electron density.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] At larger scales it includes experimental tools such as orientational imaging to examine the relative orientations at the grain boundary in materials.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] Crystallography plays a key role in many areas of biology, chemistry, and physics, as well as in emerging developments in these fields.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] Before the 20th century, the study of crystals was based on physical measurements of their geometry using a goniometer.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] This involved measuring the angles of crystal faces relative to each other and to theoretical reference axes (crystallographic axes), and establishing the symmetry of the crystal in question.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] The position in 3D space of each crystal face is plotted on a stereographic net such as a Wulff net or Lambert net.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] The pole to each face is plotted on the net.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] Each point is labelled with its Miller index.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] The final plot allows the symmetry of the crystal to be established.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] The discovery of X-rays and electrons in the last decade of the 19th century enabled the determination of crystal structures on the atomic scale, which brought about the modern era of crystallography.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] The first X-ray diffraction experiment was conducted in 1912 by Max von Laue, while electron diffraction was first realized in 1927 in the Davisson–Germer experiment and parallel work by George Paget Thomson and Alexander Reid.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] These developed into the two main branches of crystallography, X-ray crystallography and electron diffraction.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] The quality and throughput of solving crystal structures greatly improved in the second half of the 20th century, with the developments of customized instruments and phasing algorithms.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] Nowadays, crystallography is an interdisciplinary field, supporting theoretical and experimental discoveries in various domains.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] Modern-day scientific instruments for crystallography vary from laboratory-sized equipment, such as diffractometers and electron microscopes, to dedicated large facilities, such as photoinjectors, synchrotron light sources and free-electron lasers.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] Crystallographic methods depend mainly on analysis of the diffraction patterns of a sample targeted by a beam of some type.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] X-rays are most commonly used; other beams used include electrons or neutrons.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] Crystallographers often explicitly state the type of beam used, as in the terms *X-ray diffraction, neutron diffraction* and *electron diffraction*.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] These three types of radiation interact with the specimen in different ways.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] It is hard to focus x-rays or neutrons, but since electrons are charged they can be focused and are used in electron microscopes to produce magnified images.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] There are many ways that transmission electron microscopy and related techniques such as scanning transmission electron microscopy, high-resolution electron microscopy can be used to obtain images with in many cases atomic resolution from which crystallographic information can be obtained.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] There are also other methods such as low-energy electron diffraction, low-energy electron microscopy and reflection high-energy electron diffraction which can be used to obtain crystallographic information about surfaces.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] Crystallography is used by materials scientists to characterize different materials.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] In single crystals, the effects of the crystalline arrangement of atoms is often easy to see macroscopically because the natural shapes of crystals reflect the atomic structure.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] In addition, physical properties are often controlled by crystalline defects.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] The understanding of crystal structures is an important prerequisite for understanding crystallographic defects.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] Most materials do not occur as a single crystal, but are poly-crystalline in nature (they exist as an aggregate of small crystals with different orientations).
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] As such, powder diffraction techniques, which take diffraction patterns of samples with a large number of crystals, play an important role in structural determination.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] Other physical properties are also linked to crystallography.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] For example, the minerals in clay form small, flat, platelike structures.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] Clay can be easily deformed because the platelike particles can slip along each other in the plane of the plates, yet remain strongly connected in the direction perpendicular to the plates.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] Such mechanisms can be studied by crystallographic texture measurements.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] Crystallographic studies help elucidate the relationship between a material's structure and its properties, aiding in developing new materials with tailored characteristics.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] This understanding is crucial in various fields, including metallurgy, geology, and materials science.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] Advancements in crystallographic techniques, such as electron diffraction and X-ray crystallography, continue to expand our understanding of material behavior at the atomic level.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] In another example, iron transforms from a body-centered cubic (bcc) structure called ferrite to a face-centered cubic (fcc) structure called austenite when it is heated.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] The fcc structure is a close-packed structure unlike the bcc structure; thus the volume of the iron decreases when this transformation occurs.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] Crystallography is useful in phase identification.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] When manufacturing or using a material, it is generally desirable to know what compounds and what phases are present in the material, as their composition, structure and proportions will influence the material's properties.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] Each phase has a characteristic arrangement of atoms.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] X-ray or neutron diffraction can be used to identify which structures are present in the material, and thus which compounds are present.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] Crystallography covers the enumeration of the symmetry patterns which can be formed by atoms in a crystal and for this reason is related to group theory.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] X-ray crystallography is the primary method for determining the molecular conformations of biological macromolecules, particularly protein and nucleic acids such as DNA and RNA.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] The first crystal structure of a macromolecule was solved in 1958, a three-dimensional model of the myoglobin molecule obtained by X-ray analysis.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] Electron diffraction has been used to determine some protein structures, most notably membrane proteins and viral capsids.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] Macromolecular structures determined through X-ray crystallography (and other techniques) are housed in the Protein Data Bank (PDB)–a freely accessible repository for the structures of proteins and other biological macromolecules.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] There are many molecular graphics codes available for visualising these structures.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] The *International Tables for Crystallography* is an eight-book series that outlines the standard notations for formatting, describing and testing crystals.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] The series contains books that covers analysis methods and the mathematical procedures for determining organic structure through x-ray crystallography, electron diffraction, and neutron diffraction.
[src:american-mineralogist/crystallography] The International tables are focused on procedures, techniques and descriptions and do not list the physical properties of individual crystals themselves.
[src:american-mineralogist/de-gruyter] Known as De Gruyter until 2024, it merged its operations with those of the Dutch publisher Brill Publishers, forming De Gruyter Brill.
[src:american-mineralogist/de-gruyter] The roots of the company go back to 1749 when Frederick the Great granted the Königliche Realschule in Berlin the royal privilege to open a bookstore and "to publish good and useful books".
[src:american-mineralogist/de-gruyter] In 1800, the store was taken over by Georg Reimer (1776–1842), operating as the *Reimer'sche Buchhandlung* from 1817, while the school's press eventually became the *Georg Reimer Verlag*.
[src:american-mineralogist/de-gruyter] From 1816, Reimer used a representative palace at Wilhelmstraße 73 in Berlin for his family and the publishing house, whereby the wings contained his print shop and press.
[src:american-mineralogist/de-gruyter] The building later served as the Palace of the Reich President.
[src:american-mineralogist/de-gruyter] Born in Ruhrort in 1862, Walter de Gruyter took a position with Reimer Verlag in 1894.
[src:american-mineralogist/de-gruyter] By 1897, at the age of 35, he had become sole proprietor of the hundred-year-old company then known for publishing the works of German romantics such as Johann Gottlieb Fichte, Friedrich Schleiermacher, and Heinrich von Kleist.
[src:american-mineralogist/de-gruyter] De Gruyter later acquired four other publishing houses – Göschen, Guttentag, Trübner, and Veit – and, in 1919, merged them into one: *Vereinigung wissenschaftlicher Verleger Walter de Gruyter & Co*., located in Genthiner Straße, where it is still headquartered today.
[src:american-mineralogist/de-gruyter] The four publishers specialized in philosophy, theology, German literature, medicine, mathematics, engineering, law, political science, and natural science, and it is for many classics in these fields that de Gruyter is still known today.
[src:american-mineralogist/de-gruyter] By the time he died in 1924, Walter de Gruyter had created one of the largest modern publishing houses in Europe.
[src:american-mineralogist/de-gruyter] De Gruyter's son-in-law, Herbert Cram (1893–1967) succeeded him in the management of the company and it continues to be family-owned.
[src:american-mineralogist/de-gruyter] During World War II, the roof and top floor of the de Gruyter building were destroyed and the basement warehouse flooded, but the building itself survived.
[src:american-mineralogist/de-gruyter] On 14 May 1945, the publisher again registered for trading and was the first publisher in the British zone to receive a license.
[src:american-mineralogist/de-gruyter] The company became Walter de Gruyter GmbH in 2012.
[src:american-mineralogist/de-gruyter] In addition to its headquarters in Berlin, De Gruyter maintains offices around the globe, namely in Munich, Vienna, Basel, Warsaw, Boston, and Beijing.
[src:american-mineralogist/de-gruyter] In October 2023, it was announced that De Gruyter would acquire the Dutch publisher Brill for €51.1 million, forming the new company De Gruyter Brill, by the second quarter of 2024.
[src:american-mineralogist/de-gruyter] De Gruyter is one of thirteen publishers to participate in the Knowledge Unlatched pilot, a global library consortium approach to funding open access books.
[src:american-mineralogist/de-gruyter] The publisher also undertakes major long-term scholarly projects such as the Oßmannstedter Ausgabe, the complete critical edition of Christoph Martin Wieland's works.
[src:american-mineralogist/editors-in-chief] An **editor-in-chief** (**EIC**), also known as **lead editor**, **chief editor**, **executive editor**, or simply **editor** is a publication's editorial leader who has final responsibility for its operations and policies.
[src:american-mineralogist/editors-in-chief] The editor-in-chief heads all departments of the organization and is held accountable for delegating tasks to staff members and managing them.
[src:american-mineralogist/editors-in-chief] The term is often used at newspapers, magazines, yearbooks, and television news programs.
[src:american-mineralogist/editors-in-chief] The editor-in-chief is commonly the link between the publisher or proprietor and the editorial staff.
[src:american-mineralogist/editors-in-chief] The term is also applied to academic journals, where the editor-in-chief gives the ultimate decision whether a submitted manuscript will be published.
[src:american-mineralogist/editors-in-chief] This decision is made by the editor-in-chief after seeking input from reviewers selected on the basis of relevant expertise.
[src:american-mineralogist/editors-in-chief] For larger journals, the decision is often upon the recommendation of one of several associate editors who each have responsibility for a fraction of the submitted manuscripts.
[src:american-mineralogist/european-journal-of-mineralogy] This is a list of academic journals, monographic series, and other serials published by E.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Geochemistry emerged as a separate discipline after major laboratories were established, starting with the United States Geological Survey (USGS) in 1884, which began systematic surveys of the chemistry of rocks and minerals.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The chief USGS chemist, Frank Wigglesworth Clarke, noted that the elements generally decrease in abundance as their atomic weights increase, and summarized the work on elemental abundance in *The Data of Geochemistry*.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The composition of meteorites was investigated and compared to terrestrial rocks as early as 1850.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Farrington hypothesised that, although there were differences, the relative abundances should still be the same.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] This was the beginnings of the field of cosmochemistry and has contributed much of what we know about the formation of the Earth and the Solar System.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In the early 20th century, Max von Laue and William L.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Bragg showed that X-ray scattering could be used to determine the structures of crystals.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In the 1920s and 1930s, Victor Goldschmidt and associates at the University of Oslo applied these methods to many common minerals and formulated a set of rules for how elements are grouped.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Goldschmidt published this work in the series *Geochemische Verteilungsgesetze der Elemente* [Geochemical Laws of the Distribution of Elements].
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The research of Manfred Schidlowski from the 1960s to around the year 2002 was concerned with the biochemistry of the Early Earth with a focus on isotope-biogeochemistry and the evidence of the earliest life processes in Precambrian.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The building blocks of materials are the chemical elements.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] These can be identified by their atomic number Z, which is the number of protons in the nucleus.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] An element can have more than one value for N, the number of neutrons in the nucleus.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The sum of these is the mass number, which is roughly equal to the atomic mass.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Atoms with the same atomic number but different neutron numbers are called isotopes.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] A given isotope is identified by a letter for the element preceded by a superscript for the mass number.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] For example, two common isotopes of chlorine are 35Cl and 37Cl.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] There are about 1700 known combinations of Z and N, of which only about 260 are stable.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] However, most of the unstable isotopes do not occur in nature.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In geochemistry, stable isotopes are used to trace chemical pathways and reactions, while radioactive isotopes are primarily used to date samples.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The chemical behavior of an atom – its affinity for other elements and the type of bonds it forms – is determined by the arrangement of electrons in orbitals, particularly the outermost (valence) electrons.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] These arrangements are reflected in the position of elements in the periodic table.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Based on position, the elements fall into the broad groups of alkali metals, alkaline earth metals, transition metals, semi-metals (also known as metalloids), halogens, noble gases, lanthanides and actinides.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Another useful classification scheme for geochemistry is the Goldschmidt classification, which places the elements into four main groups.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] *Lithophiles* combine easily with oxygen.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] These elements, which include Na, K, Si, Al, Ti, Mg and Ca, dominate in the Earth's crust, forming silicates and other oxides.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] *Siderophile* elements (Fe, Co, Ni, Pt, Re, Os) have an affinity for iron and tend to concentrate in the core.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] *Chalcophile* elements (Cu, Ag, Zn, Pb, S) form sulfides; and *atmophile* elements (O, N, H and noble gases) dominate the atmosphere.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Within each group, some elements are refractory, remaining stable at high temperatures, while others are volatile, evaporating more easily, so heating can separate them.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The chemical composition of the Earth and other bodies is determined by two opposing processes: differentiation and mixing.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In the Earth's mantle, differentiation occurs at mid-ocean ridges through partial melting, with more refractory materials remaining at the base of the lithosphere while the remainder rises to form basalt.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] After an oceanic plate descends into the mantle, convection eventually mixes the two parts together.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Erosion differentiates granite, separating it into clay on the ocean floor, sandstone on the edge of the continent, and dissolved minerals in ocean waters.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Metamorphism and anatexis (partial melting of crustal rocks) can mix these elements together again.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In the ocean, biological organisms can cause chemical differentiation, while dissolution of the organisms and their wastes can mix the materials again.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] A major source of differentiation is fractionation, an unequal distribution of elements and isotopes.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] This can be the result of chemical reactions, phase changes, kinetic effects, or radioactivity.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] On the largest scale, *planetary differentiation* is a physical and chemical separation of a planet into chemically distinct regions.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] For example, the terrestrial planets formed iron-rich cores and silicate-rich mantles and crusts.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In the Earth's mantle, the primary source of chemical differentiation is partial melting, particularly near mid-ocean ridges.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] This can occur when the solid is heterogeneous or a solid solution, and part of the melt is separated from the solid.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The process is known as *equilibrium* or *batch* melting if the solid and melt remain in equilibrium until the moment that the melt is removed, and *fractional* or *Rayleigh* melting if it is removed continuously.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Isotopic fractionation can have mass-dependent and mass-independent forms.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Molecules with heavier isotopes have lower ground state energies and are therefore more stable.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] As a result, chemical reactions show a small isotope dependence, with heavier isotopes preferring species or compounds with a higher oxidation state; and in phase changes, heavier isotopes tend to concentrate in the heavier phases.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Mass-dependent fractionation is largest in light elements because the difference in masses is a larger fraction of the total mass.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Ratios between isotopes are generally compared to a standard.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] For example, sulfur has four stable isotopes, of which the two most common are 32S and 34S.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] where *R*s is the same ratio for a standard.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Because the differences are small, the ratio is multiplied by 1000 to make it parts per thousand (referred to as parts per mil).
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In the liquid-vapor phase transition for water, *a*l-v at 20 degrees Celsius is 1.0098 for 18O and 1.084 for 2H.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In general, fractionation is greater at lower temperatures.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] When there is no equilibrium between phases or chemical compounds, *kinetic fractionation* can occur.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] For example, at interfaces between liquid water and air, the forward reaction is enhanced if the humidity of the air is less than 100% or the water vapor is moved by a wind.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Kinetic fractionation generally is enhanced compared to equilibrium fractionation and depends on factors such as reaction rate, reaction pathway and bond energy.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Since lighter isotopes generally have weaker bonds, they tend to react faster and enrich the reaction products.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Biological fractionation is a form of kinetic fractionation since reactions tend to be in one direction.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Biological organisms prefer lighter isotopes because there is a lower energy cost in breaking energy bonds.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In addition to the previously mentioned factors, the environment and species of the organism can have a large effect on the fractionation.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Through a variety of physical and chemical processes, chemical elements change in concentration and move around in what are called *geochemical cycles*.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] An understanding of these changes requires both detailed observation and theoretical models.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Each chemical compound, element or isotope has a concentration that is a function *C*(**r**,*t*) of position and time, but it is impractical to model the full variability.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Instead, in an approach borrowed from chemical engineering, geochemists average the concentration over regions of the Earth called *geochemical reservoirs*.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The choice of reservoir depends on the problem; for example, the ocean may be a single reservoir or be split into multiple reservoirs.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In a type of model called a *box model*, a reservoir is represented by a box with inputs and outputs.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Geochemical models generally involve feedback.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In the simplest case of a linear cycle, either the input or the output from a reservoir is proportional to the concentration.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] For example, salt is removed from the ocean by formation of evaporites, and given a constant rate of evaporation in evaporite basins, the rate of removal of salt should be proportional to its concentration.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] This expresses the fact that any change in mass must be balanced by changes in the input or output.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] On a time scale of *t* = 1/k, the system approaches a steady state in which *C*steady = *a*/*k*.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] where *I* and *O* are the input and output rates.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In the above example, the steady-state input and output rates are both equal to *a*, so τres = 1/*k*.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] If the input and output rates are nonlinear functions of *C*, they may still be closely balanced over time scales much greater than the residence time; otherwise, there will be large fluctuations in *C*.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In that case, the system is always close to a steady-state and the lowest order expansion of the mass balance equation will lead to a linear equation like Equation (**1**).
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In most systems, one or both of the input and output depend on *C*, resulting in feedback that tends to maintain the steady-state.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] If an external forcing perturbs the system, it will return to the steady-state on a time scale of 1/*k*.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The composition of the Solar System is similar to that of many other stars, and aside from small anomalies it can be assumed to have formed from a solar nebula that had a uniform composition, and the composition of the Sun's photosphere is similar to that of the rest of the Solar System.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The composition of the photosphere is determined by fitting the absorption lines in its spectrum to models of the Sun's atmosphere.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] By far the largest two elements by fraction of total mass are hydrogen (74.9%) and helium (23.8%), with all the remaining elements contributing just 1.3%.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] There is a general trend of exponential decrease in abundance with increasing atomic number, although elements with even atomic number are more common than their odd-numbered neighbors (the Oddo–Harkins rule).
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Compared to the overall trend, lithium, boron and beryllium are depleted and iron is anomalously enriched.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The pattern of elemental abundance is mainly due to two factors.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The hydrogen, helium, and some of the lithium were formed in about 20 minutes after the Big Bang, while the rest were created in the interiors of stars.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Meteorites come in a variety of compositions, but chemical analysis can determine whether they were once in planetesimals that melted or differentiated.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Chondrites are undifferentiated and have round mineral inclusions called chondrules.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] With the ages of 4.56 billion years, they date to the early solar system.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] A particular kind, the CI chondrite, has a composition that closely matches that of the Sun's photosphere, except for depletion of some volatiles (H, He, C, N, O) and a group of elements (Li, B, Be) that are destroyed by nucleosynthesis in the Sun.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Because of the latter group, CI chondrites are considered a better match for the composition of the early Solar System.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Moreover, the chemical analysis of CI chondrites is more accurate than for the photosphere, so it is generally used as the source for chemical abundance, despite their rareness (only five have been recovered on Earth).
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The planets of the Solar System are divided into two groups: the four inner planets are the terrestrial planets (Mercury, Venus, Earth and Mars), with relatively small sizes and rocky surfaces.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The four outer planets are the giant planets, which are dominated by hydrogen and helium and have lower mean densities.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] These can be further subdivided into the gas giants (Jupiter and Saturn) and the ice giants (Uranus and Neptune) that have large icy cores.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Most of our direct information on the composition of the giant planets is from spectroscopy.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Since the 1930s, Jupiter was known to contain hydrogen, methane and ammonium.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In the 1960s, interferometry greatly increased the resolution and sensitivity of spectral analysis, allowing the identification of a much greater collection of molecules including ethane, acetylene, water and carbon monoxide.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] However, Earth-based spectroscopy becomes increasingly difficult with more remote planets, since the reflected light of the Sun is much dimmer; and spectroscopic analysis of light from the planets can only be used to detect vibrations of molecules, which are in the infrared frequency range.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] This constrains the abundances of the elements H, C and N.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Two other elements are detected: phosphorus in the gas phosphine (PH3) and germanium in germane (GeH4).
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The helium atom has vibrations in the ultraviolet range, which is strongly absorbed by the atmospheres of the outer planets and Earth.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Thus, despite its abundance, helium was only detected once spacecraft were sent to the outer planets, and then only indirectly through collision-induced absorption in hydrogen molecules.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Further information on Jupiter was obtained from the *Galileo* probe when it was sent into the atmosphere in 1995; and the final mission of the Cassini probe in 2017 was to enter the atmosphere of Saturn.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Spectroscopic methods only penetrate the atmospheres of Jupiter and Saturn to depths where the pressure is about equal to 1 bar, approximately Earth's atmospheric pressure at sea level.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The Galileo probe penetrated to 22 bars.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] This is a small fraction of the planet, which is expected to reach pressures of over 40 Mbar.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] To constrain the composition in the interior, thermodynamic models are constructed using the information on temperature from infrared emission spectra and equations of state for the likely compositions.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] High-pressure experiments predict that hydrogen will be a metallic liquid in the interior of Jupiter and Saturn, while in Uranus and Neptune it remains in the molecular state.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Estimates also depend on models for the formation of the planets.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Condensation of the presolar nebula would result in a gaseous planet with the same composition as the Sun, but the planets could also have formed when a solid core captured nebular gas.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In current models, the four giant planets have cores of rock and ice that are roughly the same size, but the proportion of hydrogen and helium decreases from about 300 Earth masses in Jupiter to 75 in Saturn and just a few in Uranus and Neptune.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Thus, while the gas giants are primarily composed of hydrogen and helium, the ice giants are primarily composed of heavier elements (O, C, N, S), primarily in the form of water, methane, and ammonia.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The surfaces are cold enough for molecular hydrogen to be liquid, so much of each planet is likely a hydrogen ocean overlaying one of heavier compounds.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Outside the core, Jupiter has a mantle of liquid metallic hydrogen and an atmosphere of molecular hydrogen and helium.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Metallic hydrogen does not mix well with helium, and in Saturn, it may form a separate layer below the metallic hydrogen.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Terrestrial planets are believed to have come from the same nebular material as the giant planets, but they have lost most of the lighter elements and have different histories.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Planets closer to the Sun might be expected to have a higher fraction of refractory elements, but if their later stages of formation involved collisions of large objects with orbits that sampled different parts of the Solar System, there could be little systematic dependence on position.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Direct information on Mars, Venus and Mercury largely comes from spacecraft missions.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Using gamma-ray spectrometers, the composition of the crust of Mars has been measured by the Mars Odyssey orbiter, the crust of Venus by some of the Venera missions to Venus, and the crust of Mercury by the *MESSENGER* spacecraft.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Additional information on Mars comes from meteorites that have landed on Earth (the Shergottites, Nakhlites, and Chassignites, collectively known as SNC meteorites).
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Abundances are also constrained by the masses of the planets, while the internal distribution of elements is constrained by their moments of inertia.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The planets condensed from the solar nebula, and much of the details of their composition are determined by fractionation as they cooled.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The phases that condense fall into five groups.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] First to condense are materials rich in refractory elements such as Ca and Al.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] These are followed by nickel and iron, then magnesium silicates.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Below about 700 kelvins (700 K), FeS and volatile-rich metals and silicates form a fourth group, and in the fifth group FeO enter the magnesium silicates.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The compositions of the planets and the Moon are *chondritic*, meaning that within each group the ratios between elements are the same as in carbonaceous chondrites.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The estimates of planetary compositions depend on the model used.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In the *equilibrium condensation* model, each planet was formed from a *feeding zone* in which the compositions of solids were determined by the temperature in that zone.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The greatest problem with this theory is that volatiles would not condense, so the planets would have no atmospheres and Earth no atmosphere.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In *chondritic mixing* models, the compositions of chondrites are used to estimate planetary compositions.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] For example, one model mixes two components, one with the composition of C1 chondrites and one with just the refractory components of C1 chondrites.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In another model, the abundances of the five fractionation groups are estimated using an index element for each group.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] For the most refractory group, uranium is used; iron for the second; the ratios of potassium and thallium to uranium for the next two; and the molar ratio FeO/(FeO+MgO) for the last.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Using thermal and seismic models along with heat flow and density, Fe can be constrained to within 10 percent on Earth, Venus, and Mercury.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] U can be constrained within about 30% on Earth, but its abundance on other planets is based on "educated guesses".
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] One difficulty with this model is that there may be significant errors in its prediction of volatile abundances because some volatiles are only partially condensed.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The more common rock constituents are nearly all oxides; chlorides, sulfides and fluorides are the only important exceptions to this and their total amount in any rock is usually much less than 1%.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Clarke had calculated that a little more than 47% of the Earth's crust consists of oxygen.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] It occurs principally in combination as oxides, of which the chief are silica, alumina, iron oxides, and various carbonates (calcium carbonate, magnesium carbonate, sodium carbonate, and potassium carbonate).
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The silica functions principally as an acid, forming silicates, and all the commonest minerals of igneous rocks are of this nature.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] All the other constituents occur only in very small quantities, usually much less than 1%.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] These oxides combine in a haphazard way.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] For example, potash (potassium carbonate) and soda (sodium carbonate) combine to produce feldspars.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In some cases, they may take other forms, such as nepheline, leucite, and muscovite, but in the great majority of instances they are found as feldspar.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Phosphoric acid with lime (calcium carbonate) forms apatite.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Titanium dioxide with ferrous oxide gives rise to ilmenite.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Magnesium carbonate and iron oxides with silica crystallize as olivine or enstatite, or with alumina and lime form the complex ferromagnesian silicates of which the pyroxenes, amphiboles, and biotites are the chief.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Any excess of silica above what is required to neutralize the bases will separate out as quartz; excess of alumina crystallizes as corundum.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] These must be regarded only as general tendencies.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] It is possible, by rock analysis, to say approximately what minerals the rock contains, but there are numerous exceptions to any rule.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Except in acid or siliceous igneous rocks containing greater than 66% of silica, known as felsic rocks, quartz is not abundant in igneous rocks.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In basic rocks (containing 20% of silica or less) it is rare for them to contain as much silicon, these are referred to as mafic rocks.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] If magnesium and iron are above average while silica is low, olivine may be expected; where silica is present in greater quantity over ferromagnesian minerals, such as augite, hornblende, enstatite or biotite, occur rather than olivine.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Unless potash is high and silica relatively low, leucite will not be present, for leucite does not occur with free quartz.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Nepheline, likewise, is usually found in rocks with much soda and comparatively little silica.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] With high alkalis, soda-bearing pyroxenes and amphiboles may be present.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The lower the percentage of silica and alkali's, the greater is the prevalence of plagioclase feldspar as contracted with soda or potash feldspar.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Earth's crust is composed of 90% silicate minerals and their abundance in the Earth is as follows: plagioclase feldspar (39%), alkali feldspar (12%), quartz (12%), pyroxene (11%), amphiboles (5%), micas (5%), clay minerals (5%); the remaining silicate minerals make up another 3% of Earth's crust.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Only 8% of the Earth is composed of non-silicate minerals such as carbonates, oxides, and sulfides.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The other determining factor, namely the physical conditions attending consolidation, plays, on the whole, a smaller part, yet is by no means negligible.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Certain minerals are practically confined to deep-seated intrusive rocks, e.g., microcline, muscovite, diallage.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Leucite is very rare in plutonic masses; many minerals have special peculiarities in microscopic character according to whether they crystallized in-depth or near the surface, e.g., hypersthene, orthoclase, quartz.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In this connection, we may repeat what has been said above about the corrosion of porphyritic minerals in igneous rocks.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In rhyolites and trachytes, early crystals of hornblende and biotite may be found in great numbers partially converted into augite and magnetite.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Hornblende and biotite were stable under the pressures and other conditions below the surface, but unstable at higher levels.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In the ground-mass of these rocks, augite is almost universally present.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] But the plutonic representatives of the same magma, granite, and syenite contain biotite and hornblende far more commonly than augite.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Those rocks that contain the most silica, and on crystallizing yield free quartz, form a group generally designated the "felsic" rocks.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Those again that contain the least silica and most magnesia and iron, so that quartz is absent while olivine is usually abundant, form the "mafic" group.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The "intermediate" rocks include those characterized by the general absence of both quartz and olivine.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] An important subdivision of these contains a very high percentage of alkalis, especially soda, and consequently has minerals such as nepheline and leucite not common in other rocks.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] It is often separated from the others as the "alkali" or "soda" rocks, and there is a corresponding series of mafic rocks.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Lastly, a small sub-group rich in olivine and without feldspar has been called the "ultramafic" rocks.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] They have very low percentages of silica but much iron and magnesia.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Except these last, practically all rocks contain felspars or feldspathoid minerals.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In the acid rocks, the common feldspars are orthoclase, perthite, microcline, and oligoclase—all having much silica and alkalis.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In the mafic rocks labradorite, anorthite, and bytownite prevail, being rich in lime and poor in silica, potash, and soda.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Augite is the most common ferromagnesian in mafic rocks, but biotite and hornblende are on the whole more frequent in felsic rocks.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Rocks that contain leucite or nepheline, either partly or wholly replacing felspar, are not included in this table.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] They are essentially of intermediate or of mafic character.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] We might in consequence regard them as varieties of syenite, diorite, gabbro, etc., in which feldspathoid minerals occur, and indeed there are many transitions between syenites of ordinary type and nepheline — or leucite — syenite, and between gabbro or dolerite and theralite or essexite.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] But, as many minerals develop in these "alkali" rocks that are uncommon elsewhere, it is convenient in a purely formal classification like that outlined here to treat the whole assemblage as a distinct series.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] This classification is based essentially on the mineralogical constitution of the igneous rocks.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Any chemical distinctions between the different groups, though implied, are relegated to a subordinate position.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] It is admittedly artificial, but it has grown up with the growth of the science and is still adopted as the basis on which more minute subdivisions are erected.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The subdivisions are by no means of equal value.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The syenites, for example, and the peridotites, are far less important than the granites, diorites, and gabbros.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Moreover, the effusive andesites do not always correspond to the plutonic diorites but partly also to the gabbros.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] As the different kinds of rock, regarded as aggregates of minerals, pass gradually into one another, transitional types are very common and are often so important as to receive special names.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The quartz-syenites and nordmarkites may be interposed between granite and syenite, the tonalites and adamellites between granite and diorite, the monzonites between syenite and diorite, norites and hyperites between diorite and gabbro, and so on.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Trace metals readily form complexes with major ions in the ocean, including hydroxide, carbonate, and chloride and their chemical speciation changes depending on whether the environment is oxidized or reduced.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Benjamin (2002) defines complexes of metals with more than one type of ligand, other than water, as mixed-ligand-complexes.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In some cases, a ligand contains more than one *donor* atom, forming very strong complexes, also called chelates (the ligand is the chelator).
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] One of the most common chelators is EDTA (ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid), which can replace six molecules of water and form strong bonds with metals that have a plus two charge.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] With stronger complexation, lower activity of the free metal ion is observed.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] One consequence of the lower reactivity of complexed metals compared to the same concentration of free metal is that the chelation tends to stabilize metals in the aqueous solution instead of in solids.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Concentrations of the trace metals cadmium, copper, molybdenum, manganese, rhenium, uranium and vanadium in sediments record the redox history of the oceans.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Within aquatic environments, cadmium(II) can either be in the form CdCl+(aq) in oxic waters or CdS(s) in a reduced environment.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Thus, higher concentrations of Cd in marine sediments may indicate low redox potential conditions in the past.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] For copper(II), a prevalent form is CuCl+(aq) within oxic environments and CuS(s) and Cu2S within reduced environments.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The reduced seawater environment leads to two possible oxidation states of copper, Cu(I) and Cu(II).
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Molybdenum is present as the Mo(VI) oxidation state as MoO42−(aq) in oxic environments.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Mo(V) and Mo(IV) are present in reduced environments in the forms MoO2+(aq) and MoS2(s).
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Rhenium is present as the Re(VII) oxidation state as ReO4− within oxic conditions, but is reduced to Re(IV) which may form ReO2 or ReS2.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Uranium is in oxidation state VI in UO2(CO3)34−(aq) and is found in the reduced form UO2(s).
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Vanadium is in several forms in oxidation state V(V); HVO42− and H2VO4−.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Its reduced forms can include VO2+, VO(OH)3−, and V(OH)3.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] These relative dominance of these species depends on pH.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In the water column of the ocean or deep lakes, vertical profiles of dissolved trace metals are characterized as following *conservative–type*, *nutrient–type*, or *scavenged–type* distributions.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Across these three distributions, trace metals have different residence times and are used to varying extents by planktonic microorganisms.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Trace metals with conservative-type distributions have high concentrations relative to their biological use.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] One example of a trace metal with a conservative-type distribution is molybdenum.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] It has a residence time within the oceans of around 8 × 105 years and is generally present as the molybdate anion (MoO42−).
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Molybdenum interacts weakly with particles and displays an almost uniform vertical profile in the ocean.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Relative to the abundance of molybdenum in the ocean, the amount required as a metal cofactor for enzymes in marine phytoplankton is negligible.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Trace metals with nutrient-type distributions are strongly associated with the internal cycles of particulate organic matter, especially the assimilation by plankton.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The lowest dissolved concentrations of these metals are at the surface of the ocean, where they are assimilated by plankton.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] As dissolution and decomposition occur at greater depths, concentrations of these trace metals increase.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Residence times of these metals, such as zinc, are several thousand to one hundred thousand years.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Finally, an example of a scavenged-type trace metal is aluminium, which has strong interactions with particles as well as a short residence time in the ocean.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The residence times of scavenged-type trace metals are around 100 to 1000 years.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The concentrations of these metals are highest around bottom sediments, hydrothermal vents, and rivers.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] For aluminium, atmospheric dust provides the greatest source of external inputs into the ocean.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Iron and copper show hybrid distributions in the ocean.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] They are influenced by recycling and intense scavenging.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Iron is a limiting nutrient in vast areas of the oceans and is found in high abundance along with manganese near hydrothermal vents.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Here, many iron precipitates are found, mostly in the forms of iron sulfides and oxidized iron oxyhydroxide compounds.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Concentrations of iron near hydrothermal vents can be up to one million times the concentrations found in the open ocean.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Using electrochemical techniques, it is possible to show that bioactive trace metals (zinc, cobalt, cadmium, iron, and copper) are bound by organic ligands in surface seawater.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] These ligand complexes serve to lower the bioavailability of trace metals within the ocean.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] For example, copper, which may be toxic to open ocean phytoplankton and bacteria, can form organic complexes.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] The formation of these complexes reduces the concentrations of bioavailable inorganic complexes of copper that could be toxic to sea life at high concentrations.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] Unlike copper, zinc toxicity in marine phytoplankton is low and there is no advantage to increasing the organic binding of Zn2+.
[src:american-mineralogist/geochemistry] In high-nutrient, low-chlorophyll regions, iron is the limiting nutrient, with the dominant species being strong organic complexes of Fe(III).
[src:american-mineralogist/georef] The **GeoRef** database is a bibliographic database that indexes scientific literature in the geosciences, including geology.
[src:american-mineralogist/georef] Coverage ranges from 1666 to the present for North American literature, and 1933 to the present for the rest of the world.
[src:american-mineralogist/georef] It currently contains more than 4.3 million references.
[src:american-mineralogist/georef] It is widely considered one of the preeminent literature databases for those studying the earth sciences.
[src:american-mineralogist/georef] It is produced by the American Geosciences Institute, which was known as the American Geological Institute until October 2011.
[src:american-mineralogist/georef] "To maintain the database, GeoRef editor/indexers regularly scan more than 3,500 journals in 40 languages as well as new books, maps, and reports.
[src:american-mineralogist/georef] They record the bibliographic data for each document and assign index terms to describe it.
[src:american-mineralogist/georef] Print publications that correspond to GeoRef are Bibliography and Index of North American Geology; Bibliography of Theses in Geology; and the Geophysical Abstracts, Bibliography and Index of Geology Exclusive of North America.
